definition.value: A role borne by a person who is employed by health care organization.
A dental finding that one or more surfaces of a tooth have been restored.
A dental finding that a dental procedure has been performed on a patient's mouth.
A restored tooth surface that forms the buccal surface of a restored tooth.
A restored tooth surface that forms the distal surface of a restored tooth.
A restored tooth surface that forms the incisal surface of a restored tooth.
A restored tooth surface that forms the labial surface of a restored tooth.
A restored tooth surface that forms the lingual surface of a restored tooth.
A restored tooth surface that forms the mesial surface of a restored tooth.
A restored tooth surface that forms the occlusal surface of a restored tooth.
A surgical endodontic procedure involving a multi-root tooth in which the decayed root and its related coronal portion are removed to the furcation (area of bone loss).
A restored tooth in which the tooth's pulp is removed and replaced by dental restoration material.
A tooth that has been modified in some way as the result of some surgical dental procedure.
A surgical endodontic procedure in which infected pulp is removed from a tooth in order to give the remaining pulp room to swell.
A tooth that has been surgically extracted from a patient's mouth.
A restored tooth surface that forms the lip-facing or cheek-facing surface of a restored tooth.
A restored tooth in which some portion of the tooth's root or pulp has been replaced by dental restoration material as a result of the tooth undergoing an endodontic restorative procedure.

A restored tooth in which some portion of enamel in the tooth's crown has been restored by dental restoration material as the result of the tooth undergoing either a crown procedure or intracoronal restoration procedure.
A coronally restored tooth in which all or part of the natural dental crown is repalced by an artificial crown as a result of the tooth undergoing an crown procedure.

A coronally restored tooth in which dental restoration material is placed into a site that is located in the crown of the tooth as the result of the tooth undergoing an intracoronal restoration procedure.

A coronally restored tooth in which a thin layer of material (i.e., a veneer) has been placed over one or more surfaces of the tooth as a result of the tooth undergoing a veneer restoration procedure.
An endodontic restorative procedure during which a tooth's root tip is removed and a root end cavity is prepared and filled with dental restoration material.
A tooth restoration procedure during which some portion of the tooth's root or pulp is replaced by dental restoration material.
A surgical dental procedure that is performed on the pulp chamber and/or root canal of a tooth, or a part thereof.
A surgical endodontic procure during which a root is removed from a multi-root tooth.
A dental procedure during which some part of the mouth is replaced by or fitted for a prothesis.
A prosthodontics procedure during which a prosthesis is permanently attached to some part of the mouth.
A prosthodontics procedure during which a removable prosthesis is either constructed or fitted to the patient's mouth.
A fixed prosthodontics procedure in which a dental implant is permanently attached to the jaw.
A removable prosthodontics procedure in which the prosthesis being constructed or fitted replaces all of the patient's teeth.
A removable prosthodontics procedure in which the prosthesis being constructed or fitted replaces some but not all of the patient's teeth.
A fixed partial denture that is suppored and retained by underlying tissue and one or more dental implants.
A partial denture that is designed and constructed to be removed readily from the mouth.
A prosthesis that replaces all the natural teeth and associated structures in either the maxilla or mandible (or both).
A complete denture that is perminately attached to the mouth.
A complete denture that replaces all the natural teeth and associated structures in both the maxilla and mandible.
A complete denture that replaces all the natural teeth and associated structures in the mandible.
A prosthetic tooth with an anchoring structure surgically implanted beneath the mucosal or periosteal layer or in the bone.
A disorder that is part of a tooth.

value.value: A mechanical tooth lesion formed as a result of the tooth being fatigued, flexed, and deformed by biomechanical loading of the tooth. Tooth abfactions are primarily found in the cervical region of the tooth.

definition.value: A tooth friction lesion that is caused by either the functional (e.g., mastication) or parafunctional movement of the jaws (e.g., bruxism).
A non-carious tooth lesion that is formed as result of the tooth being exposed to acids.
A tooth friction lesion that is formed as result of some abrasive process.
A carious tooth lesion that resulted from some tooth decay but the infected region is not currently decaying.
A carious tooth lesion that is currently undergoing the process of tooth decay.
A carious tooth lesion that is found only within the enamel.
A carious tooth legion that has extended to the dentine.
